This Python package synthesizes a Dutch corpus comprising 13 files. The files contain sentences in various templates, where in each template the matrix verb is intransitive. The name of each file begins with a number denoting the template: 1, the subject noun phrase contains a subordinate clause; 2, the subject noun phrase contains a prepositional phrase; and 3, the subject noun phrase contains a subordinate clause, and the verb phrase in the matrix clause contains an adverb phrase. The template number is followed by a series of the letters 's' and 'p', representing the grammatical numbers 'singular' and 'plural', respectively. Each letter denotes the grammatical number of the content word with the same index as the letter. That is, each combination of a number and a sequence of the letters 's' and 'p' represents one condition.

Users of the package may synthesize a corpus either by executing the package from the command-line interface (python3 -m synthesis <output_directory> <sample_size>), or by importing the package within a Python script and calling the main(...) function (from synthesis import main). Note that executing the package from the command-line interface is equivalent to calling the main(...) function. In either case, two arguments are required: the first argument is the path where the package saves the corpus; and the second argument is the number of sentences per condition (per file). Passing a sample size that is less than or equal to 0 causes the package to generate all possible sentences using all possible permutations of the content words found in the subpackage 'data'.